=> The Canonical Constructor of a Record Class

    -> In a Record class, Java automatically generates a constructor that takes all the components as parameters.

    -> This constructor is called the "canonical constructor".

    -> For example, in the Record class:

            record RectangleUsingRecord(double length, double width) { }

    -> The canonical constructor would be:

            public RectangleUsingRecord(double length, double width) {
                this.length = length;
                this.width = width;
            }

    -> This constructor initializes all the fields of the record.

    -> You can also define your own canonical constructor if you want to add validation or additional logic during object creation.

=> Custom Canonical Constructor in Record Class

    -> If you want to add custom logic during object creation, you can define your own canonical constructor in a Record class.

    -> For example:

            record RectangleUsingRecord(double length, double width) {

                public RectangleUsingRecord {
                    if (length <= 0 || width <= 0) {
                        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Length and width must be positive");
                    }
                }
            }

    -> In this example, we have defined a custom canonical constructor that checks if the length and width are positive values.

    -> If the validation fails, it throws an IllegalArgumentException.

    -> This allows you to enforce constraints on the data being stored in the record while still benefiting from the automatic generation of other methods.

=> Alternative Record Constructors

    -> In addition to the canonical constructor, you can also define alternative constructors in a Record class.

    -> Alternative constructors are defined using the "this" keyword to call the canonical constructor.

    -> For example:

            record RectangleUsingRecord(double length, double width) {

                public RectangleUsingRecord(double side) {
                    this(side, side); // Calls the canonical constructor
                }
            }

    -> In this example, we have defined an alternative constructor that takes a single parameter "side" and creates a square by calling the canonical constructor with the same value for length and width.

    -> This allows you to provide multiple ways to create instances of the record while still maintaining immutability and simplicity.

=> Explicit Declaration of Record Class Members

    -> In a Record class, you can explicitly declare:
            -> constructors
            -> methods
            -> static fields and methods
            -> nested types

    -> But the record header defines the only instance fields allowed.
    -> The components declared in the record header are implicitly:
            -> private
            -> final
            -> part of the canonical constructor
            -> included in equals(), hashCode(), and toString()
    
    -> You cannot declare additional instance fields in a Record class outside of the record header.

    -> Invalid example (compile error):

            record RectangleUsingRecord(double length, double width) {
                private int area; // not allowed: extra instance field
            }
    -> You can explicitly declare any of the members derived from the header, such as the public accessor methods that correspond to the record class's components.
    -> Correct approach: use a method to compute derived values.

    -> Example:

            record RectangleUsingRecord(double length, double width) {

                public double area() {
                    return length * width;
                }
            }
    -> You can declare static fields, static initializers, and static methods in a record class, and they behave as they would in a normal class, for example:

            record RectangleUsingRecord(double length, double width) {

                //static field
                public static String shapeType = "Rectangle";

                //static Initializer
                static {        
                    System.out.println("Static initializer called");
                }
                
                //static method
                public static void printShapeType() {
                    System.out.println(shapeType);
                }
            }

    -> You cannot declare instance variables (non-static fields) or instance initializers in a record class.
            record Rectangle(double length, double width) {

                // Field declarations must be static:
                BiFunction<Double, Double, Double> diagonal;

                // Instance initializers are not allowed in records:
                {
                        diagonal = (x, y) -> Math.sqrt(x*x + y*y);
                }
            }

    -> You can declare instance methods in a record class, independent of whether you implement your own accessor methods. 
            record Rectangle(double length, double width) {

                // Nested record class
                record RotationAngle(double angle) {
                        public RotationAngle {  // Compact constructor
                                angle = Math.toRadians(angle);
                        }
                }
                
                // Public instance method
                public Rectangle getRotatedRectangleBoundingBox(double angle) {
                        RotationAngle ra = new RotationAngle(angle);
                        double x = Math.abs(length * Math.cos(ra.angle())) +
                                Math.abs(width * Math.sin(ra.angle()));
                        double y = Math.abs(length * Math.sin(ra.angle())) +
                                Math.abs(width * Math.cos(ra.angle()));
                        return new Rectangle(x, y);
                }
            }

            -> Compact constructor:
                -> Theory:
                   -> Records automatically generate a canonical constructor that takes all components as parameters and assigns them to the fields.
                   -> To customize the constructor logic (e.g., for validation or transformation), you can define a compact constructor.
                   -> A compact constructor has the same name as the record and no parameter list; the parameters are implicitly provided.
                   -> Inside the compact constructor, you can access the component parameters directly and perform validations or transformations.
                   -> You cannot return a value from a compact constructor; it's for setup only.

                -> Example 1: Validation in compact constructor
                        record Rectangle(double length, double width) {
                                public Rectangle {
                                        // length and width are automatically available as parameters
                                        if (length <= 0 || width <= 0) {
                                                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Length and width must be positive");
                                        }
                                        // No return statement; just validation
                                }
                        }

                -> Example 2: Transformation in compact constructor
                        record RotationAngle(double angle) {
                                public RotationAngle {
                                        // angle is automatically available as a parameter
                                        if (angle < 0 || angle >= 360) {
                                                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Angle must be between 0 and 360 degrees");
                                        }
                                        // Suppose user gives angle in degrees, but we want to store it in radians internally
                                        this.angle = Math.toRadians(angle);
                                }
                        }


    -> Usage example:

            public class Main {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                    RectangleUsingRecord rect = new RectangleUsingRecord(4, 5);
                    System.out.println(rect.length()); // 4.0
                    System.out.println(rect.width());  // 5.0
                    System.out.println(rect.area());   // 20.0
                }
            }

    -> Explanation:
            -> `length` and `width` are record components, not regular instance fields.
            -> They are automatically created and cannot be re-declared inside the record body.
            -> `area()` is a computed method, so it adds behavior without adding mutable instance state.
            -> This keeps the record immutable and simple.

=> Features of Record Classes

    -> Record classes are a special kind of class in Java that provide a compact syntax for declaring classes that are transparent holders for shallowly immutable data.

    -> Key features of record classes include:

        1. Compact Syntax:
            -> Record classes have a concise syntax that allows you to declare a class with its components (fields) in a single line.

        2. Immutable Data:
            -> The fields of a record class are implicitly final, making the instances of the record immutable.

        3. Auto-generated Methods:
            -> Java automatically generates several methods for record classes, including:
                -> A canonical constructor that initializes all fields.
                -> Accessor methods for each field (with the same name as the field).
                -> equals() and hashCode() methods based on the fields.
                -> A toString() method that includes the class name and field values.

        4. No Additional Instance Fields:
            -> You cannot declare additional instance fields in a record class outside of the record header.

        5. Support for Static Members:
            -> You can declare static fields, static initializers, and static methods in a record class.

        6. Nested Types:
            -> You can declare nested types (classes, interfaces, enums) within a record class.

        7. Custom Constructors and Methods:
            -> You can define custom constructors (including compact constructors) and instance methods to add behavior to your record class while maintaining immutability.
        
        8. Create Generic record classes:
            -> Record classes can be generic, allowing you to define records that can hold different types of data.
            -> Example:

                    record Pair<T, U>(T first, U second) { }
                    where
                        T and U are type parameters that can be specified when creating an instance of the Pair record.
                        Example usage:

                            Pair<String, Integer> pair = new Pair<>("Hello", 42);
                            System.out.println(pair.first()); // Output: Hello
                            System.out.println(pair.second()); // Output: 42

        9. Implementing one or more interfaces:
            -> Record classes can implement interfaces, allowing them to be used in contexts where a specific interface type is required.
            -> Example:

                    record Point(int x, int y) implements Comparable<Point> {
                        @Override
                        public int compareTo(Point other) {
                            return Integer.compare(this.x * this.x + this.y * this.y,
                                                   other.x * other.x + other.y * other.y);
                        }
                    }
                    In this example, the Point record implements the Comparable interface, allowing instances of Point to be compared based on their distance from the origin.

        10. Cannot Extend Other Classes:
            -> Record classes cannot extend other classes (they implicitly extend java.lang.Record), but they can implement interfaces.
                    Example:
                                record Circle(double radius) extends Shape { } // This will cause a compile error
                                record Circle(double radius) implements Drawable { } // This is valid

        11. Cannot be Abstract or Final:
            -> Record classes cannot be declared as abstract or final, as they are implicitly final and cannot be subclassed.
                    Example:
                                abstract record AbstractRecord(int value) { } // This will cause a compile error
                                final record FinalRecord(int value) { } // This will also cause a compile error

        12. Cannot Declare Instance Initializers:
            -> Record classes cannot have instance initializers, as they are designed to be immutable and all initialization should be done through the canonical constructor or compact constructor.
                    Example:
                                record Rectangle(double length, double width) {
                                    {
                                        // This will cause a compile error
                                        System.out.println("Instance initializer");
                                    }
                                }
        13. Cannot Declare Instance Fields:
            -> Record classes cannot declare additional instance fields outside of the record header, as all fields must be defined in the header to be part of the canonical constructor and auto-generated methods.
                    Example:
                                record Rectangle(double length, double width) {
                                    private int area; // This will cause a compile error
                                }
        14. Cannot Declare Instance Methods with the Same Name as Components:
            -> Record classes cannot declare instance methods that have the same name as the record components, as this would conflict with the auto-generated accessor methods.
                    Example:
                                record Rectangle(double length, double width) {
                                    public double length() { // This will cause a compile error
                                        return length * 2; // This is not allowed
                                    }
                                }
        15. Cannot Declare Static Methods with the Same Name as Components:
            -> Record classes cannot declare static methods that have the same name as the record components, as this would also conflict with the auto-generated accessor methods.
                    Example:
                                record Rectangle(double length, double width) {
                                    public static double length() { // This will cause a compile error
                                        return 0; // This is not allowed
                                    }
                                }
        16. Cannot Declare Nested Records with the Same Name as the Enclosing Record:
            -> Record classes cannot declare nested records that have the same name as the enclosing record, as this would cause a naming conflict.
                    Example:
                                record Rectangle(double length, double width) {
                                    record Rectangle(double side) { // This will cause a compile error
                                        public Rectangle {
                                            this(side, side);
                                        }
                                    }
                                }
        17. Cannot Declare Local Records:
            -> Record classes cannot be declared as local classes within a method, as they are intended to be top-level or static nested types.
                    Example:
                                public void someMethod() {
                                    record LocalRecord(int value) { } // This will cause a compile error
                                }
        18. Cannot Declare Anonymous Records:
            -> Record classes cannot be declared as anonymous classes, as they require a name and a specific structure defined by the record header.
                    Example:
                                Object obj = new record(int value) { }; // This will cause a compile error
        19. Cannot Declare Records in Interfaces or Enums:
            -> Record classes cannot be declared within interfaces or enums, as they are meant to be standalone types.
                    Example:
                                interface Shape {
                                    record Circle(double radius) { } // This will cause a compile error
                                }
                                enum Color {
                                    RED, GREEN, BLUE;
                                    record Shade(int intensity) { } // This will also cause a compile error
                                }
        20. Cannot Declare Records in Local or Anonymous Classes:
            -> Record classes cannot be declared within local or anonymous classes, as they are intended to be top-level or static nested types.
                    Example:
                                public void someMethod() {
                                    class LocalClass {
                                        record LocalRecord(int value) { } // This will cause a compile error
                                    }
                                }
        21. Cannot Declare Records in Static Initializers:
            -> Record classes cannot be declared within static initializers, as they are meant to be top-level or static nested types.
                    Example:
                                static {
                                    record StaticRecord(int value) { } // This will cause a compile error
                                }
        22. Cannot Declare Records in Instance Initializers:
            -> Record classes cannot be declared within instance initializers, as they are designed to be immutable and all initialization should be done through the canonical constructor or compact constructor.
                    Example:
                                record Rectangle(double length, double width) {
                                    {
                                        record InnerRecord(int value) { } // This will cause a compile error
                                    }
                                }
        23. Can annotate a record class and its components with annotations:
            -> Record classes and their components can be annotated with annotations to provide additional metadata or behavior.
                    Example:
                                @Deprecated
                                record OldRecord(@Deprecated String oldField) { }

    -> Overall, record classes provide a convenient way to create simple data carrier classes without the need for boilerplate code, while still allowing for customization and additional functionality when needed.           

=> Record Classes and Sealed Classes and Interfaces

    -> Record classes can be declared as sealed, which means they can only be extended by a specific set of classes.

    -> Sealed classes and interfaces are a feature in Java that allows you to control which classes can extend or implement them.

    -> When a record class is declared as sealed, it must specify the permitted subclasses using the "permits" clause.

    -> Example of a sealed record class:

            public sealed record Shape(String name) permits Circle, Rectangle { }

            public final class Circle extends Shape {
                public Circle() {
                    super("Circle");
                }
            }

            public final class Rectangle extends Shape {
                public Rectangle() {
                    super("Rectangle");
                }
            }

    -> In this example, the Shape record is declared as sealed and permits only the Circle and Rectangle classes to extend it.

    -> This allows you to have a controlled hierarchy of shapes while still benefiting from the immutability and concise syntax of records.

=> Static Members of Inner Classes

    -> Prior to Java 16, inner classes (non-static nested classes) could not have static members unless that member is a constant (static final field initialized with a compile-time constant expression) variable.

    -> From Java 16 onwards, inner classes in Java can have static members, but they must be declared as static nested classes.

    -> A static nested class is a nested class that is declared static, which means it does not have access to the instance variables and methods of the outer class.

