=> Differences Between the Serialization of Records and Ordinary Objects

    -> Records in Java are designed to be simple data carriers, and they have a specific serialization mechanism that differs from ordinary objects.

    -> When a record is serialized, only the components (fields) defined in the record header are serialized. The auto-generated methods (like equals(), hashCode(), toString()) and any additional methods or static members are not serialized.

    -> In contrast, when an ordinary object is serialized, all non-transient instance fields are serialized, regardless of whether they are defined in a specific header or not.

    -> Additionally, records have a built-in serialization mechanism that ensures that the canonical constructor is used during deserialization, which helps maintain the immutability and integrity of the record instances.

    -> Overall, the serialization of records focuses on the components defined in the record header, while ordinary objects serialize all non-transient instance fields.

=> APIs related to Record Classes

    -> Java provides several APIs that are related to record classes, including:

        1. java.lang.Record:
            -> This is the base class for all record classes in Java. It provides methods for accessing the components of a record and for comparing records.

        2. java.lang.reflect.RecordComponent:
            -> This class represents a component of a record class. It provides methods for accessing the name, type, and annotations of a record component.

        3. java.lang.reflect.RecordComponent.getRecordComponents():
            -> This method returns an array of RecordComponent objects representing the components of a record class.

        4. java.lang.reflect.RecordComponent.getAccessor():
            -> This method returns the accessor method for a given record component.

        5. java.lang.reflect.RecordComponent.getType():
            -> This method returns the type of a given record component.

        6. java.lang.reflect.RecordComponent.getName():
            -> This method returns the name of a given record component.

    -> These APIs allow you to introspect and manipulate record classes and their components at runtime, providing flexibility and control over how you work with records in your applications.
